Raw dev notes -- February 2026

Wrapped up a shipping cost calculator for a logistics company. Their sales team was
spending too much time looking up rates in Excel spreadsheets -- cross-referencing
zone tables, weight brackets, surcharge rules. Slow and error-prone, especially for
multi-item shipments where you need to calculate dimensional weight and check pallet
thresholds.

Built it as a React + TypeScript desktop app. You plug in package dimensions and weight,
select a destination, and get an instant breakdown: base rate, surcharges, dimensional
weight comparison, and a PDF quote ready to send to the customer. The app also gives
smart tips -- like 'reduce one dimension by 3cm to avoid the oversized surcharge.'

This month was mostly about hardening the codebase:
- Broke the monolithic App.tsx into 6 focused components
- Fixed all 52 TypeScript strict-mode errors (the codebase was 'any'-heavy before)
- Wrote 74 tests with vitest covering different weight ranges, zones, and edge cases
- Added localStorage persistence so the form state survives app restarts
- Built a custom app icon for the Windows EXE build

The pricing logic was the tricky part. Dimensional weight vs actual weight, pallet
surcharges that kick in at specific thresholds, zone-based rate tables that change
quarterly. Getting the business rules exactly right mattered -- one wrong calculation
and the client quotes the wrong price to their customer.

Struggles: ESLint v9 dropped during the refactor and broke the existing config. Spent
way too long on that. Also, npm output in GitBash is unreliable when captured -- I had
to redirect to temp files, which is a running theme on my Windows setup.

Not the flashiest project, but there's something satisfying about building a tool that
replaces a manual process with something instant and accurate. The 74-test suite gives
me confidence that the pricing logic is correct, which is the whole point.
